              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2960285192003510400">O thy Gods of Olympus! Why must thou taste the sweet tenderness of thy bosom? For all that is around us is finite. <br/><br/>By far, the best work of literature I have ever had the pleasure of reading in all of my 30 years of existence on this wretched planet of ours. To merely gaze upon this translated work of art is an honor in itself. Just picture the generations of people who never knew of its existence since 1937, and think how one is immensely privileged to live in a time, where it is readily availa</span>
  <span id="freeText2960285192003510400" style="display:none">O thy Gods of Olympus! Why must thou taste the sweet tenderness of thy bosom? For all that is around us is finite. <br /><br />By far, the best work of literature I have ever had the pleasure of reading in all of my 30 years of existence on this wretched planet of ours. To merely gaze upon this translated work of art is an honor in itself. Just picture the generations of people who never knew of its existence since 1937, and think how one is immensely privileged to live in a time, where it is readily available for one to consume for one’s very soul. <br /><br />The pleasure I’ve had reading this work of art is nothing short of orgasmic, and Fallada’s usage of ever moving cinematography was pure bliss. A triumph! Indeed a triumph! Thank you Rudolf Wilhelm Friedrich Ditzen, thank you. May you Rest In Peace O’ troubled but masterful soul. </span>
