    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3192812498" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3192812498" />
    <a title="Agnes Wattrang" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/33063505-agnes-wattrang"><img alt="Agnes Wattrang" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/f_50x66-6a03a5c12233c941481992b82eea8d23.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3192812498?book_show_action=true">Feb 16, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Agnes Wattrang" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Agnes Wattrang" href="/user/show/33063505-agnes-wattrang">Agnes Wattrang</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780093080400" href="/book/show/3386324-wolf-among-wolves">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3192812498" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8818356265186087140">Hans Fallada’s &quot;Wolf among Wolves&quot; takes place in the Weimar Republic during the second half of 1923 and the premier half of 1924. At this time, there is a galloping inflation in Germany, partly due to the war debt imposed on the country after the First World War. In the beginning of the novel, in July 1923, the dollar stands at 414 000 marks. The financial situation would become aggravated to the extent that a dollar would cost more than four trillion marks as of November 1923. At the end of th</span>
  <span id="freeText8818356265186087140" style="display:none">Hans Fallada’s "Wolf among Wolves" takes place in the Weimar Republic during the second half of 1923 and the premier half of 1924. At this time, there is a galloping inflation in Germany, partly due to the war debt imposed on the country after the First World War. In the beginning of the novel, in July 1923, the dollar stands at 414 000 marks. The financial situation would become aggravated to the extent that a dollar would cost more than four trillion marks as of November 1923. At the end of that month, a new currency, the Rentenmark, is introduced, which eventually ends the hyperinflation.<br /><br />As a consequence of the inflation, a large number of the German population have difficulties affording a living. People witness their savings become worthless in less than no time. Unemployment is rampant in the cities whereas work opportunities present in the rural parts of the country. Yet people make for the cities where the lower class steadily grows.<br /><br />It is in this context the reader is introduced to one of the main characters of the novel, Wolfgang Pagel, or simply Wolf. Pagel is a young man in his early twenties and a former second lieutenant in the First World War. His family consists of his mother only, the aged Frau Pagel, since his father, Edmund Pagel, an ex-attaché and a fairly successful painter, died in an accident a long time ago. In spite of the fact that he is of a comfortably situated Berlin family, Wolfgang tries to earn his living through gambling. He exhibits personality traits associated with gambling: risk-seeking and irresponsible and at the same time calculating and stubborn. He often speaks of getting a proper job, for instance as a taxi driver, but never sets about it. One can sense a sort of guilt within Wolfgang’s actions, mostly towards his girlfriend, Petra, whom he constantly lets down, but perhaps also towards his mother. The latter adores her son but cannot stand Petra whom she thinks is not good enough for him. Wolfgang, on his side, cannot accept the way his mother treats Petra and the fact that she dislikes his gambling habit. Therefore, he leaves his mother’s posh flat at Tannenstrasse to rent a room together with Petra in some poor district of Berlin.<br /><br />The paths of Wolfgang and Petra were crossed by mere chance, at a time when Petra used to walk the streets in order to earn her living. She comes from a working-class family and was kicked out of her home by her loveless mother. Similar to Wolfgang, Petra has a somewhat complex personality: naïve and submissive yet industrious and responsible, she is a young woman trying to find her way in a ruthless world. As the novel begins, Petra and Wolfgang are supposed to get married, only Wolfgang does not have enough money for the marriage license. He is thus forced to pawn everything they own, including Petra’s clothes, to afford the fare to visit an old acquaintance whom he thinks will lend him some money. In the meantime, Petra, whose remaining clothes consist of one of Wolfgang discarded overcoats, is caught by the police for disorderly behaviour. She has not done any harm, but because of her appearance, and onset dizziness due to hunger, which the policeman mistakes for drunkenness, she is considered to be peace-disturbing. She is placed in custody at Alexanderplatz, and as it turns out, is refused bail.<br /><br />Parallel to the story of Wolfgang and Petra runs that of Rittmeister Joachim von Prackwitz, lessee at the manor Neulohe, situated in eastern Germany, near the Polish border. von Prackwitz and Pagel belonged to the same regiment during the war and the two of them will coincidentally meet again in Berlin, in the end of July 1923. At the time of their reunion, the Rittmeister is accompanied by his wartime subordinate, Oberleutnant von Studmann, who nowadays works as a reception manager at a Berlin hotel. von Prackwitz manages to persuade both von Studmann and Pagel to join him at Neulohe, as he is in need of assistance during harvest time.<br /><br />Back at the manor, several intrigues are in progress: the greedy owner of Neulohe, Geheimrat von Teschow, who happens to be von Prackwitz’s father-in-law, tries to skin the Rittmeister on his share of the harvest, a stir arises when the inhabitants at Neulohe find out that a band of convicts are hired from a nearby prison to assist with the gathering of the harvest, the Rittmeister’s underaged daughter has an affair with a lieutenant involved in the organization of a revolt against the government, a putsch, etc.<br /><br />Life on the countryside turns out to be favourable to Pagel, who quits gambling and starts to develop a sense of responsibility as time passes. Meanwhile, Petra is discharged and begins to work in a thrift store in Berlin. Moreover, she is pregnant with Wolfgang’s child and determined to raise the child by her own.<br /><br />After spending the autumn months working at Neulohe, Pagel is brought back to Berlin at the end of the year. With some effort, he manages to regain Petra’s confidence and the two of them even become reconciled with Wolfgang’s mother, who reluctantly decides to accept Petra as part of the family. In what follows, Wolfgang enters university, aiming for a medical degree, while Petra stays at home taking care of their newborn son.<br /><br />The novel thus ends happily for the young couple; Pagel is freed from his gambling addiction and comes to realize what he really wants to work with, whereas Petra, saved from living on the streets, rejoices at a quiet life together with Wolfgang and their son. As a reader, one may object that such a happy ending is not entirely convincing given how the story started out. Nor is the transformation which Wolfgang undergoes in less than a year, from being an egocentric high roller to becoming a responsible father and husband, whose highest priority is to care for the sick. On the other hand, a lot occur in the lead-up to the moment when Wolfgang and Petra reunite. There are many accounts of their individual struggle and hardship throughout the novel and it is clear from the beginning that the couple’s mutual affection, as well as need for one another, is strong. One must also bear in mind that this is a story about two young people in their formative years. Taking this into account, the ending becomes more plausible.<br /><br />The title line “Wolf among Wolves”, and allusions to it, reappears throughout the novel, and at such passages almost always provokes the thought of fight or survival. For instance, Wolfgang formulates it as “Man against man, wolf against wolves, he must make his decision if he was to respect himself.” (p. 766), apropos holding on to one’s principles. Other examples are: “Whoever didn’t steal got robbed. Whoever didn’t bite got bitten.” (p. 400) or “Life is no holiday; it’s an extremely deceitful business, and whoever doesn’t cheat others get cheated himself.” (p. 449).<br /><br />Did Fallada himself nurture such a cynical and violent outlook on life? We don’t know, since we cannot ask him. I, however, do not believe that this reflects the author’s personal viewpoint, it is rather a way to raise tension and to create rhythm. Of course, it also says something about the general feeling in the German society when the economic crisis was at its peak.<br /><br />Regarding the style of the novel, Fallada writes a clear, rather laconic, prose, which makes reading agreeable. As a writer, he is highly capable of creating atmospheres and building up tension. With that said, however, this novel does not reach the same levels as "Alone in Berlin" concerning these two latter qualities. In fact, I find parts of it to be quite boring, serving more as preliminaries to the more interesting parts to come, rather than having a value of their own. <br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="8818356265186087140" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

