  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_4208312596" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/4208312596" />
    <a title="Peter Lindstrom" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/42621288-peter-lindstrom"><img alt="Peter Lindstrom" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1430352535p2/42621288.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/4208312596?book_show_action=true">Aug 30, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Peter Lindstrom" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Peter Lindstrom" href="/user/show/42621288-peter-lindstrom">Peter Lindstrom</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780093080400" href="/book/show/3386324-wolf-among-wolves">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer4208312596" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7558210630508005030">Published in 1938, under the watchful eyes of Joseph Goebbels, Fallada cleverly avoided censorship from the Hitler regime by documenting the biggest failure of the Weimar Republic, the government&apos;s response to the inflation crisis. Thus, Fallada could write in his documentary style, while the ruling Nazis could promote his book (and they did) as an indictment of German democracy. Because there was nothing directly promoting Hitler, this book was an unexpected bestseller in the US, UK and Canada,</span>
  <span id="freeText7558210630508005030" style="display:none">Published in 1938, under the watchful eyes of Joseph Goebbels, Fallada cleverly avoided censorship from the Hitler regime by documenting the biggest failure of the Weimar Republic, the government's response to the inflation crisis. Thus, Fallada could write in his documentary style, while the ruling Nazis could promote his book (and they did) as an indictment of German democracy. Because there was nothing directly promoting Hitler, this book was an unexpected bestseller in the US, UK and Canada, boosting Fallada's much depleted bank account, saving him from a fate he was dreading, applying for work within the regime.<br /><br />In this new and very compelling translation, a reader can experience Fallada's unique style that combined reporting, childlike storytelling and detailing that has been described as Dickensian. This novel is also different from Fallada's other works first because the author's style here is strictly realistic, having none of the trapping of his "New Objectivity" works (which not surprising, as both that artistic movement and Fallada were fiercely anti-authoritarian, one reason why Goebbels was always watching.)<br /><br />But the most unique feature of this novel is how the story is told: while the action takes place over one year, more than a third of the book's opening covers a single day in central Berlin, with the remaining 364 days taking place at a large farming operation in a very rural community.<br /><br />Though many characters take the story in a number of directions, the focus is on Wolfgang Pagel, the "wolf" of the title. He's a young man from an upper middle class family, a decommissioned officer disillusioned by life who needs to both grow up and find some purpose. Summarizing the plot would be pointless because the action is centered on how Weimar's hyperinflation pitted Germans against each other. With just a few exceptions, Fallada's characters in both big city and rural regions are shown as grasping "wolves" quick to feast on the misfortunes of even their loved ones so that they might profit.<br /><br />A nice twist is the nature of Fallada's hero, Wolfgang Pagel: for nearly the entire the novel, he is arrogant and full of himself. Yet, after a woman he loves is literally taken from him, he decides Berlin is too poisonous and agrees to a position on a farm—where he learns the rural citizens are just as corrupt as the urbanites he just escaped. Worse, since the farm folk consider themselves superior to the city dwellers, they are not only arrogant, they refuse to see their own faults and often act more ruthlessly.<br /><br />Since Wolfgang Pagel is resourceful enough to uncover just how everyone is exploiting everyone else, he chooses not to profit from his situation—which he could easily do—and decides his safest option is to rise above the backstabbing. Not because Pagel thinks himself to be a good man, he reasons correctly that if people think they can exploit him, he will survive longer. Indeed, survival was the point of the 1923 hyperinflation: while Pagel may be the most moral "wolf" in this story, when he faced with two bad choices (which happens often) Pagel is not above sacrificing those he likes or pities just to save himself.<br /><br />While a little knowledge of German history in the 1920s might be helpful, it is not necessary: Fallada has been justly called a German Dickens and like "A Tale of Two Cities," you don't need to know about the French Revolution to find this story compelling.</span>
  <a data-text-id="7558210630508005030" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

