    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_272140559" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/272140559" />
    <a title="Lauren" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/735404-lauren"><img alt="Lauren" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1359660593p2/735404.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/272140559?book_show_action=true">Jun 11, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Lauren" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Lauren" href="/user/show/735404-lauren">Lauren</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780093080400" href="/book/show/3386324-wolf-among-wolves">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer272140559" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2081140416083652659">4.5 stars. This 8oo-page brick is well worth the commitment -- an intricate and devastating glimpse into the daily lives of individuals struggling through the German hyperinflation of the fall of 1923, beginning in Berlin and moving to the countryside and centering mostly on the network of friends, family, and acquaintances of the young and aimless army vet Wolfgang Pagel. Wolfgang&apos;s evolution from dissolute gambling addict, who literally sells the last of his girlfriend&apos;s clothes off her body t</span>
  <span id="freeText2081140416083652659" style="display:none">4.5 stars. This 8oo-page brick is well worth the commitment -- an intricate and devastating glimpse into the daily lives of individuals struggling through the German hyperinflation of the fall of 1923, beginning in Berlin and moving to the countryside and centering mostly on the network of friends, family, and acquaintances of the young and aimless army vet Wolfgang Pagel. Wolfgang's evolution from dissolute gambling addict, who literally sells the last of his girlfriend's clothes off her body to pay for his habit, to someone more responsible and responsive is full of revelations that resonate today, and characters that Fallada renders as fully human, capable of change and kindness but also of selfishness, pettiness, and violence. This translation is excellent - nothing stilted or disjointed, and the couple of characters who speak mostly in slang are rendered intelligently. Beyond the sub-plot about a putsch in the second half of the novel, Fallada includes only a few glancing nods at the political situation, so don't look for early Nazism to play any kind of prominent role. Even the sections set in Berlin put politics mostly in the background - this story is focused on the social and economic spheres of existence: what happens to people when money is worthless and society's morals are in constant flux. I found this more immersive and mesmerizing than Every Man Dies Alone, which is usually touted as his masterpiece. Highly recommended.</span>
  <a data-text-id="2081140416083652659" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

