    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2127826975" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2127826975" />
    <a title="Dan" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5983822-dan"><img alt="Dan" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1515415138p2/5983822.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2127826975?book_show_action=true">Dec 01, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Dan" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Dan" href="/user/show/5983822-dan">Dan</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5983822-dan?shelf=fiction">fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5983822-dan?shelf=germany">germany</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2127826975" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12603557158888869360">i gradually came to love this dark saga. it is set in 1923, and written by someone who lived and knew several aspects of life in that destabilised (and later destabilising) time. the shadow of the just-finished great war lies on some of its characters, not always a dark one, but the economic and social rug is pulled out beneath the feet of all of them by the great inflation of that year. tensions are visible which the reader knows even more completely than the writer (written 1937) will fuel dis</span>
  <span id="freeText12603557158888869360" style="display:none">i gradually came to love this dark saga. it is set in 1923, and written by someone who lived and knew several aspects of life in that destabilised (and later destabilising) time. the shadow of the just-finished great war lies on some of its characters, not always a dark one, but the economic and social rug is pulled out beneath the feet of all of them by the great inflation of that year. tensions are visible which the reader knows even more completely than the writer (written 1937) will fuel disaster. all of that's interesting, for me at least, but would not have kept a slow impatient reader like me going for 800 pages. <br /><br />greater than the chronicling of this time, and the twisting plot that builds tension throughout, were the characters. all feel human and real, all have hard flaws and usually slighter virtues and work within their own perceived worlds in a way that fallada renders hypnotically. dickens without the coincidences (though slightly dickensy ending, which apparently he may have regretted), tolstoy across the social spectrum, thomas mann with a bit more action. but not 5 stars from me, because 800pp is just too dear in terms of hours. i love great editors as much as great authors.<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="12603557158888869360" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

